    {
      "topic_id": "newtons_laws",
      "title": "Force & Newton's Laws",
      "order": 2,
      "explanation": {
        "simple": "Force is a push or pull that can change an object's motion. Newton gave us three laws: (1) Objects stay at rest or in motion unless a force acts on them (inertia). (2) F = ma — force equals mass times acceleration. (3) For every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction. These three laws explain almost all everyday motion!",
        "advanced": "Newton's laws form the foundation of classical mechanics. The first law defines inertial frames and the concept of net force. The second law, F_net = dp/dt (generalized form), relates force to rate of change of momentum; for constant mass, F = ma. The third law establishes force pairs — the forces are equal, opposite, and act on different bodies. Free body diagrams isolate a system and inventory all forces. Applications include friction (f = μN), tension, normal force, and gravitational force (w = mg). These laws are valid in inertial reference frames and break down at relativistic speeds or quantum scales."
      },
      "formulas": [
        {
          "name": "Newton's Second Law",
          "latex": "\\vec{F}_{net} = m\\vec{a}",
          "variables": {
            "F_net": {"description": "Net (resultant) force", "unit": "N (Newtons)"},
            "m": {"description": "Mass", "unit": "kg"},
            "a": {"description": "Acceleration", "unit": "m/s²"}
          }
        },
        {
          "name": "Weight",
          "latex": "W = mg",
          "variables": {
            "W": {"description": "Weight (gravitational force)", "unit": "N"},
            "g": {"description": "Gravitational acceleration ≈ 9.8 m/s²", "unit": "m/s²"}
          }
        },
        {
          "name": "Friction",
          "latex": "f = \\mu N",
          "variables": {
            "f": {"description": "Friction force", "unit": "N"},
            "μ": {"description": "Coefficient of friction (static or kinetic)", "unit": ""},
            "N": {"description": "Normal (contact) force", "unit": "N"}
          }
        },
        {
          "name": "Momentum",
          "latex": "\\vec{p} = m\\vec{v}",
          "variables": {
            "p": {"description": "Linear momentum", "unit": "kg·m/s"}
          }
        },
        {
          "name": "Impulse",
          "latex": "J = F \\cdot \\Delta t = \\Delta p",
          "variables": {
            "J": {"description": "Impulse", "unit": "N·s"}
          }
        },
        {
          "name": "Newton's Law of Gravitation",
          "latex": "F = \\frac{Gm_1 m_2}{r^2}",
          "variables": {
            "G": {"description": "Gravitational constant = 6.674 × 10⁻¹¹ N·m²/kg²", "unit": "N·m²/kg²"},
            "r": {"description": "Distance between centers of mass", "unit": "m"}
          }
        }
      ],
